\begin_layout Standard
The main goal of our model is to explain how consumer behaviour with respect
 to effort or investment towards their own status changes in response to
 income differences 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\equiv y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},y_{2}$
\end_inset

 are disposable incomes for the poor and rich consumers (respectively).
 A fundamental assumption for the model is that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 are fixed in the short-term horizon considered by the consumer.
 The resetting of wealth at a certain period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

 is also an intrinsic feature of the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We proceed by first discussing the degenerate case when players (consumers)
 maximise accumulated assets at an infinite horizon.
 After discussing the futility of positional competition in such a game,
 we consider the case when myopic consumers that are concerned with the
 next immediate single-period (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The Nash Equilibrium solution for this problem and its implications for
 effects of income differences are discussed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main changes that have been made to model since its previous version
 are as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
While the previous model didn't allow the time-horizons to change, the current
 model adopts a more general approach to time-horizons - letting assets
 reset at a general interval 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\tau$
\end_inset

 rather than at 
\begin_inset Formula $T=2$
\end_inset

.
 While the solution in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 does deal 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=2$
\end_inset

, a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 can be understood as more myopia (i.e.
 shorter time-horizon) for gains from positional gains in the model.
 The assumptions pertaining to the short-term horizon are detailed in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Instead of assuming a particular shape of utility function, the closed-form
 solution for the case of maximisation of assets under assumption of risk-neutra
l preferences is considered foremost.
 Utility functions with risk-aversion are to be introduced later along with
 relevant assumptions for consumer preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The martingale requirement for expected asset maximisation (simplest case)
 is discussed and the relevant assumptions are made for optimisation of
 total assets over the short-term horizon.
 Any efforts in the next period are ignored in the short-term horizon for
 the consumer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Unlike the previous model which assumed presence of calamitous risk to accumulat
ed assets, the current model interprets the long-term horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 only as the end-of-life for the consumer.
 The key feature of the model is that the consumer is unable to transfer
 her accumulated assets to the progeny.
 With this no-bequest model, the consumer banks upon entirely on the game
 of social positions at the end of her life-cycle.
 The feature accommodates the objection made by dissimilarity between social
 and economic positions - since the feature accommodates the possibility
 of a significant number of players (consumers) achieving a higher socio-economi
c position while failing to transfer their social status towards end-of-life
 (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:PopulationConstraint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for details).
 A further clarification about how the schemes of promotion and demotion
 for two players may reflect changing of proportions of rich and poor in
 the society is provided in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:PopulationConstraint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The population constraint is not imposed in the short-term for the consumers.
 Instead, we track the ratio of promotions to demotions to explain how consumer
 choices to maximise assets are driven by long-term constraints on parameters
 that control 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 - which are the promotion of demotion functions for poor and rich consumers
 (respectively) in the model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The promotion and demotion functions are assumed have a concave form - rather
 than the logistic form used in the previous version of the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"

\end_inset

Single-Period Assets Maximisation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current model uses maximisation of assets in a single period i.e.
 the consumers maximise assets acquired in the immediate next period alone
 by exercising the choice in the current period.
 The multiple-period maximisation is avoided for two reasons.
 First, the alternative to ascertain martingale conditions using a risk-neutral
 probability measure (which ensure additivity of assets accumulated over
 multiple time periods - see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "harrison1981martingales"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) in the multiple period setting does not influence the results we arrive
 at for the effects of income differences in a single-period maximisation.
 Second, the single-period assumption may allow us to relieve the risk-neutralit
y condition for the consumer's utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That the consumer horizon must be finite (if not single) for a feasible
 positional game follows from the argument that the positional game would
 be inconsequential if the poor and rich consumers optimised an infinite-horizon
 value.
 Intuitively, it is easy to see that the consumer won't engage in any short-term
 gains if they already know the long-term values of their assets.
 More formally, we can consider the long-term evaluations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

 of future assets values for the poor and rich consumers (respectively)
 so that in the long-term equilibrium, the net addition to the assets through
 the positional game would be zero.
 In this equilibrium, the poor and rich consumers would choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 (respectively) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}-\nu_{1,t}+\frac{W(\nu_{1,t})\mathscr{A}_{2}+(1-W(\nu_{1,t}))\mathscr{A}_{1}}{\delta}=\mathscr{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}-\nu_{2,t}+\frac{L(\nu_{2,t})\mathscr{A}_{1}+(1-L(\nu_{2,t}))\mathscr{A}_{2}}{\delta}=\mathscr{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

- where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},y_{2}$
\end_inset

 are incomes for poorer consumer 1 and richer consumer 2 (respectively),
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 represents the time-value of money i.e.
 a discount factor and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2,t})$
\end_inset

 are functions for promotion and demotion functions for two respective positions
 (poor and rich) in the game.
 One way this can be achieved is be having 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}=\nu_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}=\nu_{2,t}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 when consumer spends all of their income in the effort (investment) and
 their economic position remains stable (due to promotion and demotion probabili
ties implied by 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2,t})$
\end_inset

 respectively).
 As such, all possible solutions must maintain that no net value is added
 to the long-term values 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and thus positional game is inconsequential for either of the consumers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such a result seems at odds for what we observe about status competitions.
 The maximisation of terminal assets are hardly reported to represent consumer
 behaviour well (see St.
 Petersburg paradox
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SanjitDhamiBehavioural2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 In fact, the instances of economic history suggest that income differences
 that are perceived as perpetual often increase the possibilities of social
 unrest rather than assisting stable equilibria.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With consumer myopia being a better representation of the real-world conditions,
 we our attention on maximisation of assets for until the immediately next
 period.
 The single-period horizon for the consumer implies that the assets optimised
 by the consumer in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 do not include the effort or investment in the next period i.e.
 the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 should not include 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t+1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2,t+1}$
\end_inset

).
 This allows us to solve for consumer 1's strategy i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t\in[1,\tau]}$
\end_inset

 by iterations starting with period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 and finishing at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

.
 This poorer consumer in a period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 would thus need to optimise the following function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
y_{1,t}-\nu_{1,t}+\frac{W(\nu_{1,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-W(\nu_{1,t}))y_{2,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer1genoptimfunc}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}$
\end_inset

 are the incomes in a period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 is the effort in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

 is the promotion probability in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that at the end-of-life i.e.
 in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

, the consumer (a risk-neutral dynast) cannot carry over the accumulated
 assets and must spend everything on the position game - thus letting the
 assets to be augmented in the last period by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{W(y_{1,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-W(y_{2,t1}))y_{2,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer1genlastperiod}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the consumer 2 i.e.
 the richer consumer maximises the following function in every period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
y_{2,t}-\nu_{2,t}+\frac{L(\nu_{2,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-L(\nu_{2,t}))y_{1,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer2genoptimfunc}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer 2 i.e.
 the richer consumer would add the following value to her assets in the
 last period
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{W(y_{1,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-W(y_{2,t1}))y_{2,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer2genlastperiod}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To discuss the solution of the equilibrium, we consider a special case with
 two conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Stable Incomes}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - The income in every period to the consumers remains the same so that
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 With same income assumed in every period and with the maximisation of assets
 (rather than a utility that may consider satiation with assets), the asset
 increments at every period except the last period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

 are the same.
 More specifically, the consumer behaviour in every period 
\begin_inset Formula $t\ne\tau$
\end_inset

 is one where the poorer (or richer) consumer adds 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})y_{2}+(1-W(\nu_{1,t}))y_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2,t})y_{1}+(1-L(\nu_{2,t}))y_{2}$
\end_inset

) in any time period 
\begin_inset Formula $t\ne\tau$
\end_inset

 - while in the last period, the consumer sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,\tau}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2,\tau}=y_{2}$
\end_inset

 ) hoping to have 
\begin_inset Formula $W(y_{1})y_{2}+(1-W(y_{1}))y_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $L(y_{2})y_{1}+(1-L(y_{2}))y_{2}$
\end_inset

 ) in the first period (without considering the effort or investment 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,1},\nu_{2,1}$
\end_inset

 in the first period after the reset).
 The solution in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 therefore only considers two periods i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Concave promotion and demotion functions}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - A specific set of (concave) promotion and demotion functions are chosen
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1})=1-\frac{1}{\sqrt{a\nu_{1}+1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2})=\frac{1}{\sqrt{a\nu_{2}+1}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"

\end_inset

Nash Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The functions for promotion and demotion of the poor and rich consumers
 (respectively) must satisfy both of the following conditions 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
increasing (decreasing) in 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 increases while 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 decreases with higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

) and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
asymptotic to unity (zero) so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{\nu\rightarrow\infty}W(\nu)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{\nu\rightarrow\infty}L(\nu)=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the promotion and demotions functions (
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 respectively) do not represent distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 - but are binary distributions with a mean modified by 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 (see Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:wnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The expectation of promotions is therefore defined for a particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 simply as 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)(1)+(1-W(\nu))(0)$
\end_inset

 and similarly, the expected demotions are 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We choose the following single-parameter concave functions that meet the
 above criteria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
W(\nu) & =1-\frac{1}{\sqrt{a\nu+1}}\label{eq:wnu_concave}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
L(\nu) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{b\nu+1}}\label{eq:lnu_concave}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The functions in Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:wnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

