\begin_layout Standard
So far we have treated the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 as exogenous.
 One constraint on the parameters - which follows from the assumption that
 social positions are maintained in the long-term - that of a stability
 to promotions and demotions.
 The constraints on social growth have generated an interest in the economic
 literature at least since 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HarrodGrowth1958"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (also see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "scitovskyjoyless1992,HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ).
 In simple terms, the relative difference between the poor and rich - represente
d as poor and rich positions in the game - can be maintained so long as
 there is one poor or one rich person in the long-term.
 Regardless of how many consumers are rich or poor, a long-term equilibrium
 requires that the promotions balanced by demotions over a given period
 of time.
 In other words, for a life-cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and the single-periods within them (each which are represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[1,\tau]$
\end_inset

 that the consumers maximise assets over), the long-term stability of promotions
 and demotions means that the net demotions over a few life-cycles would
 balance out the promotions.
 There is no other way in which the game can be feasible to the consumers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words, the consumers moving from poor to the rich band would be
 balanced by those moving from rich to the poor band in a long-term equilibrium.
 It is important to emphasise that the two consumers we have shown behaviour
 of in the model are representative consumers and therefore, the balance
 of demotions and promotions is subject to the proportions of poor and rich
 in the population well as the changes in notions of what separates poor
 and rich (see details in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:ProportionsRichPoor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To consider what the constraint means in terms of the above model, we define
 the ratio of promotions to demotions in every period as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\rho(t) & =\frac{W(\nu_{1,t})}{L(\nu_{2,t})}\label{eq:rho_ratio}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An implicit assumption with the above definition (Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rho_ratio"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is that at any point in time, there are a certain number of consumers
 in a given period of their life-cycle (time horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

 (as respective probabilities of promotion and demotion).
 In other words, the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(t)$
\end_inset

 represents a comparison between two consumers with synchronised long-term
 and short-term horizons.
 Therefore, using the forms of 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 defined in Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:wnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W(\nu_{1}^{*}) & =1-\frac{1}{\sqrt{a\nu_{1}^{(}+1}}=1-(\frac{2\delta}{y_{2}-y_{1}})^{1/3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
L(\nu_{2}^{*}) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{b\nu_{2}^{*}+1}}=(\frac{2\delta}{y_{2}-y_{1}})^{1/3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho(t) & =(\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{2\delta})^{1/3}-1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ratio of promotions vs demotions thus depends only on income differences
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the discount factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
 As we have argued before, higher income differences 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 must increase promotions in the equilibrium.
 However, promotions in the long-term must also be balanced by demotions
 because of population stability so that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
