 In the above model - where consumer maximise expected assets in a finite-horizo
n -the constraint being met in the short-term horizon means that consumers
 adjust their expectation for future assets as the income differences rise.
 The applicability of the model with the constraint is thus limited to the
 cases when consumers alter their expectations as soon as promotions balance
 out demotions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now discuss the effect of income differences on consumer choices of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

in presence of the population constraint on parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},y_{2}$
\end_inset

